author: The Current
description:
Nanna from Of Monsters and Men sheds light on the vivid album title
Support The Current: https://support.mpr.org/youtube or hit the Thanks button

During an interview with Gannon at The Current, Nanna Bryndis Hilmarsdottir of the band Of Monsters and Men explains the meaning of the album title, "All is Love and Pain in the Mouse Parade."

Of Monsters and Men’s 2025 album, "All Is Love and Pain in the Mouse Parade," is available on Skarkali Records/Virgin Music Group.

author: The Current
description:
Watch Of Monsters and Men perform "The Towering Skyscraper at the End of the Road" live in studio
Support The Current: https://support.mpr.org/youtube or hit the Thanks button

Icelandic band Of Monsters and Men have been together for 15 years, but they took a bit of time off before recording their latest album, "All Is Love and Pain in the Mouse Parade." When the band reunited in the studio to work on the album, they rediscovered the joy of playing together.

When Of Monsters and Men visited St. Paul in November, they played two back-to-back nights at the Palace Theatre. Between those shows, Of Monsters and Men visited The Current studio to play songs from the new album. Watch and listen a performance of "The Towering Skyscraper at the End of the Road" above.

Musicians
Nanna Bryndis Hilmarsdottir - vocals, guitar
Ragnar Thorhallsson - vocals, guitar, piano
Brynjar Leifsson - guitar, vocals
Kristjan Kristjansson - bass, vocals
Arnar Hilmarsson - drums

Credits

author: The Current
description:
Watch a fun conversation with Soul Asylum recorded at The Current
Support The Current: https://support.mpr.org/youtube or hit the Thanks button

It feels like an annual tradition: longtime Minneapolis rock band Soul Asylum visit The Current studio near the end of the year to share what they've been up to recently, and 2025 is no exception. Soul Asylum's Dave Pirner, Ryan Smith and Jeremy Tappero visited The Current to play an acoustic set of songs and to share their latest updates. 

They also reflect on the late stage manager from First Avenue, Conrad Sverkerson, and the place he holds in their hearts. Soul Asylum also talk about what it was like when their song, "Somebody to Shove," was used on a several-day loop by another radio station when it was switching its format.

Watch and listen to the full interview above.

Musicians
David Pirner – lead vocals, guitar
Ryan Smith – lead guitar
Jeremy Tappero – bass
